**Deceiver’s Feat: personal only — cannot mask other creatures, mounts, or companions**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Farborn humans vs. Kin humans sidebar added (Chapter 4a) — clarifies hybrid rules for non-Kin**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Spur Tower confirmed as the Dómnathar hidden stronghold in the Deepwater Marches**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Flamewarg cults: spread from Gatefall Remnant westward into Deepwater Marches over centuries**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Titanbreed horse pricing established: 8,000–15,000 gp (hybrids); purebloods never sold**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Flamewarg Cults faction entry updated: Gatefall origin, spread to Deepwater Marches**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Deepwater Marches settlements added to Chapter 17**  |  **Author Ruling (Feb 2026 Deepwater Marches session)**

**Visetri Dwarves: confirmed as canonical spelling (replaces “Vestri” throughout Bible)**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Eternal Steppe session)**

**Each human Kin blames the others for the Shattering of Man — mutual recrimination, no subrace accepts responsibility**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Eternal Steppe session)**

**Gilded Standard Company expanded: neutral merc outfit, leader styled as Duke, defected during Running War after Deceivers ordered them as sacrificial screen, contacted Mytrone, flipped to Kin side, 1 in 10 survived**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Eternal Steppe session)**

**Gate of Fire: canonical name for the navigable pass in the Gatefall Reach between the desert and the Eternal Steppe**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Eternal Steppe session)**

**Wind-Rider / Far Rider dual naming: Pasua call them Far Riders, Mytrone call them Wind-Riders. Both names are canonical and interchangeable for the same ancient brotherhood of Mytroan lancers and Pasua mounted archers.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Running War: started in the Gatefall Reach when the Wind-Riders intercepted the Lost Third returning south, then escalated across the Eternal Steppe**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**The Scattering was ordered because the Wind-Riders would have crushed the Lost Third entirely without it**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Lost Third march route clarified: north through Oreka with the host, south through Gate of Fire back into Gatefall Reach, then west onto the Eternal Steppe**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Northern two-thirds of host: continued north, devastated Tidebloom settlements, besieged Aldenheim; survivors scattered westward after the Fall**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Scar Road: canonical Gatefall Reach landmark — the path of the original Deceiver march, still visible after 300 years**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Burnt Warrens: canonical Gatefall Reach landmark — underground burrow-forts built by scattered Deceiver warbands after Dark Dawn, extending beneath southeastern foothills and crescent forests**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Windstone Circle: canonical Gatefall Reach landmark — ring of five Giant-era standing stones on the Gatefall Grasslands, shared Mytroan-Pasua sacred site**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Kovaka watchtower destruction reconciled: towers flanking the Silence Breach were destroyed by radial force from the Breach event itself; towers along the Gap and southeastern approaches were destroyed by the advancing Deceiver army**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Gatefall Reach settlements added to Chapter 17 with full detail**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Gatefall Reach Regional Detail section added to Chapter 6**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Gatefall Reach session)**

**Flamewarg presence on Eternal Steppe: confirmed consistent — grassland transition zones are part of the steppe region**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Eternal Steppe session)**

**Domnathar Elemental Disconnection rewritten: Domnathar possess no Elemental Affinity but are NOT barred from using elemental magic. They are weaker in it than Kin races, not prohibited. Primary magic derives from Abyss Circle. Previous wording replaced.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Canon Bible audit session)**

**Death, Accounting, and Rebirth cycle: full canon section added as Chapter 4b. Three Aspects established — The One Who Listens, The One Who Judges, The One Who Teaches. Aspects are part of each Elemental Lord but separate; unknown to living Kin. Judgment measures intent and action, not outcome. No punishment/reward system — a maturation system. Soul carries forward colored instincts not memories. Cruelty not condemned but shown its full consequence so the soul self-corrects across lifetimes.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Farborn rebirth canon: Farborn have been voluntarily entering the rebirth cycle for 300 years / 6-7 generations. Soul-coloring now producing first Kin-sense flickers in current generation. Will become Fifth House of Human Kin in time. The Three Aspects accept souls from other worlds.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Dómnathar civilization expanded: Chapter 7 now includes 7a (Dómnathar-Zhuan — underground city-states, house rivalry as stabilizer, slave majority population, half-breed second class cherished and despised simultaneously, Abyssal 9 propitiated not loved, gods of hope exist only in slave whispers), 7b (the invasion was an accident — minor lords and ladies sent to die for glory stumbled through a misfired Assault Gate), 7c (cut off — Elemental Lords slammed the gate, Abyssal 9 cannot reach Oreka because Lady of Fire and Tempest hold the door, no reinforcement for 300 years), 7d (every Dómnathar considers themselves Dómnathar without exception — better dead than lesser, concept of soul-growth through rebirth is annihilation to them, tragedy at their core). Campaign implication: they are preparing to receive their gods, not launch another army.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Dómnathar Civilization session)**

**Trade and Currency: Chapter 4e added. Four pillars of long-distance trade — Halflings (open water, undisputed lords of the seas), Eruskan (rivers and waterways, shore to interior), Pekakarlik (shipbuilders and hydraulic infrastructure, the unacknowledged foundation), Visetri (overland routes, everywhere water cannot reach). Village market foundation underlies all. Currency: Titan (gold), Stone (silver), Shard (copper). Giant-era weight standard still in use — never improved upon. Kharazhad produces most trusted coinage. Four pillars are interdependent — one of the strongest forces for post-Shattering Kin cooperation.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Trade session)**

**Coming of Age and education: Chapter 4d added. All Kin share the same educational structure inherited from the Giants through the relay system. Stages: mother (birth to ~7), father (practical years), community school (~7-8), then at 13 three paths — city schools and great institutions, family craft, or apprenticeship. None lesser than others. Birthday is the ceremony — celebrated every year, marks each threshold. The moment of choosing at 13 is the true coming of age. Giant cities and Elven cities of learning are the highest tier. The shared structure is the deepest unifying thread across all Kin cultures.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Coming of Age session)**

**Religion in daily life: Chapter 4c added. Three tiers of practice — (1) Daily: million little thank yous woven into every act from waking to sleeping, no priest required, personal and constant. (2) Local shrines: at brooks, gardens, rivers, lakes, seas, forest edges, aviaries — tended by whoever uses that place, not by clergy. Shrines grow from accumulated gratitude not doctrine. (3) Seasonal solstice gatherings: always held outside in the element being honored — fields, shorelines, bonfires, windy hills. Led by local Magi who study the gods. Element is the temple. DM-facing: three hundred years of prayers to Lords who cannot fully hear them. The wind shrines are still meticulously tended. Something in every prayer feels like a letter that might not be getting through.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Lords in Daily Life session)**

**Taraf-Imro death customs: Taraf-Imro spend their lives building toward their own funeral. Annual Voice of the Dead letter — updated every year while alive, always about how specific people brought them joy and cared for them, read aloud at the funeral so every name is spoken publicly. Deceased dressed in finest, armed with tools of trade. Possessions distributed to those of greatest need so everyone goes home with something. Pyre lit at top of a hill with Voice and farewell letters tucked around it. Feast at the bottom of the hill while fire burns above. Death as completion not loss. Chosen to lead the Eke Concordant because deliberate open love generates trust that cannot be manufactured.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Eruskan culture and death customs: Two groups — Shore Eruskan (farmers, fishermen, chain tenders, close to Oreans, Lord Mayor city structure, remnant of Eke Concordant) and Trader Eruskan (live on ships, port to port, years without land). Both worship Lady of Water and Lord of Stone primarily. Burial: three day vigil, young men row raft past last chain point, raft weighted and sunk to the deep where Water and Earth meet in harmony. Trader version performed at sea with the horizon as the boundary. The young men who row do not come back unchanged. Of all Oreka’s peoples the Eruskan live closest to the rebirth cycle theology without naming it — they experience harmony as daily physical fact.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Orean death customs and governance: Orean are most scattered Human culture — small villages networked into Gatherings. Shared cemeteries across village networks. Runners dispatched day before funeral to entire Gathering. Each Meet sends food gift to grieving family. Long procession from home to cemetery. Every village has a Headman. Every Gathering has a Justice — authority activates only when needed, not permanent. Justice attends every funeral as witness. Grand Meet = all Justices convene in rare crises, choose one trusted person to lead until resolved, then dissolves. Trust earned one funeral at a time. Cannot be corrupted because it does not persist.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Mytroan death customs: Mytroan keen for the dead through vocal exaltation — grief released as pure sound into the open plain. Bodies burned and returned to the four elements. Horses pass father to son, mother to daughter — to the most similar soul not the best rider. Family tends aging horses through their own crossing. Only knowledge that can travel gets written down; everything else passes master to apprentice by demonstration. Camp grieves fully then moves because the Mytroan are the Wind of change.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Halfling death customs: Halflings see death as ephemeral and trust the cycle completely. Funerals are celebrations of life — parties with food the person loved, stories that made them laugh, neighbors invited same as family. The closing sentiment is “welcome home” not farewell. Halflings return through rebirth faster than any other race. Their faith in the cycle is the deepest in Oreka not because of doctrine but because of accumulated repetitions across many lifetimes.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Elven death customs: Elves fade physically as they approach death — body dissolves into Oreka’s elemental magic, spirit walks directly through the veil. No remains. In the months/years beforehand Elves distribute all beloved possessions to whoever is best suited to carry them forward. Receiving a crossing gift from an Elf elder is a great honor — it means the Elf saw you clearly. The grief of loving an Elf is learning to receive beautifully.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Dwarf death customs: Dwarves spend their final years creating a masterwork — the culmination of everything learned across a lifetime. Top apprentice folds master’s ashes into a memorial work after death. Dwarves grieve by speaking names and keeping lineage. In the Summer Lands Dwarves wait longest of all Kin before rebirth — they treat the accounting as an apprenticeship and question the Teachers extensively. Return with deep craft knowledge that surfaces as inexplicable intuition in the next life.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Dómnathar refusal canon: Dómnathar reject the rebirth cycle and return as undead. They never receive the Three Aspects’ teaching. A thousand-year-old Dómnathar is not wise — they are fixed. Patterns never examined, consequences never shown. Why they refuse is reserved for campaign development.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Wind Lord theology: the Youngest Brother is the quiet architect behind Kin civilization. Present at every creation act but never the named creator. Made the Stone Lord believe the succession plan (raising Kin races to replace Giants) was the Stone Lord’s own idea. Not malicious — the Wind Lord genuinely seeks harmony. His exile was a genuine mistake, not a plan. He is the trickster who finally tricked himself.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Death and Grief session)**

**Mytroan adjective standardized: Mytroan is the canonical adjective form (e.g., Mytroan capital, Mytroan lancers). Mytrone remains correct as a noun referring to the people (e.g., the Mytrone).**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Canon Bible audit session)**

**Canon Bible version bumped to v2.6**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Canon Bible audit session)**

**Creation myth of the Elves updated: Giants carved the statues; the Youngest Brother (Wind Lord) breathed life into them. Both are co-creators. Creation table updated accordingly.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Creation myth of the Dwarves: Lady of Fire attempted the same process as the Giants but fire compressed and shrank the forms, producing Dwarves. Not a failed Elf — a new thing.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Creation myth of the Halflings: The First Jest and the Price of It — full canon myth added to Chapter 2. Lady Tempest created from loneliness using silt, sand, water, and the Youngest Brother’s blessing. First Halfling died mid-joke having made his goddess smile. Now resides in the Palace of Waters. Explains Halfling humor, short stature, and devotion to making others smile.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Dwarf cultural split: Pekakarlik estrangement from Rarozhki and Visetri originated in a trade dispute involving Aldenheim. Visetri caught in the middle through delayed loyalty. Full details reserved for adventure development. A crack in the lore — do not elaborate beyond “something went wrong” in player-facing documents.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Kin migration framework established: all Kin races were raised to sustainable population levels in the Infinite Desert beside the Giants before migrating to elemental home zones. This is why Giant reverence persists across all Kin cultures. Each race migrated sequentially — Elves near-departed before Dwarves were born; a small number of Elves helped raise Dwarves. Same relay pattern continued through Halflings. Humans came last after a long gap.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Human creation expanded: Humans were designed as Giant successors as Thalorien began. Giants and Elves (with help from all Kin) attempted to create a race carrying all four elements who could guide Kin civilization. The critical distinction: Giants were elemental harmony (the held chord); Humans are elemental contrast (the song). Wind of change, rain of renewal, passionate fire, moving earth. They were not what their creators intended — and no one understood this until it was too late.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**The Great Shame of the Elves: DM-facing canon. Elves believe they failed in their duty to guide Humans, and that the suffering of the Dómnathar war is partly their responsibility. This shame drives Elven behavior toward Humans to this day — the patience, the guidance, the refusal to withdraw. Humans are unaware of this. Player-facing: Elves hold a particular unexplained tenderness for Humans. DM-facing: they are still trying to finish a job they believe they failed.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Halfling subraces defined: four subraces, all water element, indistinguishable to outside Kin. Each carries a different shade of Tempest’s loneliness at the time of creation. Water Halflings — tend Giant-forged ships, serve without recognition, loneliness of being unseen. Wind Halflings — travel most, never arrive, loneliness of perpetual motion. Fire Halflings — daring and bold, too much for the room, loneliness of feeling too deeply. Earth Halflings — travel overland, patient, loneliness of waiting. The pilgrimage belongs most naturally to the Earth Halflings.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Halfling pilgrimage canon expanded: the once-in-a-lifetime overland pilgrimage from one sea to the other is a gift to the first Halfling, who died before he could cross the world. Halflings walk overland (not through the Sea Falls) because the pilgrimage goes across the world Tempest spans, not through her domain. It is an act of showing her what the world looks like from the ground.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Mithril Legion full entry added to factions section: Visetri wandering brotherhood, oldest active fighting force on Oreka, organized into shield companies. Left side of every wagon plated in mithril — caravans circle to form a fortress when threatened. Legion doctrine: shield companies advance into hottest fights drawing all attention while caravans circle behind the enemy. Cheerfulness is genuine not a mask — born from road culture where the people in front of you right now are everything. Nothing is worse than the Legion holding long enough for a caravan to circle and prepare. The Legion was never the weapon. They were the door closing.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Three Military Orders formalized in factions section: Mithril Legion (Visetri brotherhood, well-known, player-facing), Steelward Host (Aldenheim defenders, extinct, mostly forgotten), Stone Covenant (Kin-wide army at Kharazhad, public knows it exists but not its connection to the others). Full connection revealed only at full membership.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Kin migration from the Infinite Desert: Elves left first by elemental pull — Kovaka into desert mountains, Na'wasua upward to floating islands, Pasua onto the Eternal Steppe grasslands, Hasura toward rivers and coasts (pushed into canopy by dangerous fauna). Pasua stayed longest to help raise Dwarves, joined by some Hasura and a few Na'wasua. Kovaka visited but did not stay. The relay pattern: each race helped raise the next before fully migrating.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**

**Dwarf elemental origin and culture: Dwarves absorbed Earth and Water influences during their raising (primarily by Pasua and Hasura Elves). This produced the stoic endurance that defines all three Dwarf cultures. Even the wandering Visetri express this as immovable loyalty and the Legion's forward advance — endurance made mobile.**  |  **Author Ruling (Mar 2026 Migration and Mythology session)**